<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9669938347594></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9669938347594><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=14&mid=9669938347594>NPC Hunting: Chief Gan`Shralok - Levels 17-22</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=14&mid=9669938347594#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=347><span id= >Kithias</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>12 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Aug 22nd 9:23 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.71]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ok, here is the promised guide after Trissa to take you to 22. Now that you&#8217;ve got your 16th level spells and have had a level to play with them, head on over to Kithicor during the day (go at night at your own risk) and get to the High Hold Pass zone entrance (loc: 400, 4800). Now turn around, gather shadows, and facing out to Kithicor with the zone at your back, hang a right along the zone border wall and follow it a short distance. Eventually you should come to a few orcs.<br><br>This may be important depending on the way you use this guide, but move about and count the orcs, get to know their spots and the lay of the land (again, heh, do this during the day and invisible). You will notice four spawn points total. There are two near a large tree, 1 farther back on the hill and 1 on the hill closer to the zone wall. This last one is the Chiefs spawn point. The other three can spawn anything from orcs (his followers) to fire beetles to grey wolfs and wolfs to giant bats and skeletons. Those are all Place Holders, but you should notice that they don&#8217;t roam at all, and stick to particular spots.<br><br>All right, now that you are familiar with where everything is, on to tactics. There are two that I used. First, if you have a group or feel brave, you can tackle this entire group. Pull the two orcs nearest the trees, hitting either one will bring them both. Use your favorite method: FD split the spawn, harmony/lull one of them, or just take them at the same time. Next pull the orc on the hill, not the Chief. Pull him away from the chief and back to the zone wall (where you&#8217;ll do most of your fighting, you don&#8217;t want to be deep into Kithicor). Last but not least, nail the Chief. If you can do all that within 5 to 6 minutes and still be ready, guess what, the two tree spawn points are going to be up soon. They may not always spawn orcs, but they&#8217;ll pop shortly. I was able to take the camp this way with a friend of mine. He played a bard, and was also 17. It was basically non-stop fighting, with an occasional pause for me to med up or the pet to heal up.<br><br>The second tactic, which I also used quite a bit, was soloing the Chief. To do this you&#8217;ll have to hug that zone wall close, turn to face the orc, back up on the wall as far as you can. Keep him in your line of sight, he should be in front of you and below you now. All set? Good, cast a pet, buff it and yourself (I&#8217;ll cover this later) and med to full. Ready? Send the pet in and immediately cast Engulfing Darkness. The pet and spell should land at about the same time. Now Heat Blood, Heart Flutter, Leach, and get ready for an incoming and quite pissed Chief. Yes he will be on you. Yes you will get hit for large amounts. No, you probably won&#8217;t die unless your AC is 11. Try to time your Lifedraws, and if you can get Banshee Aura, it will help quite a bit. Very soon you&#8217;ll have a very dead orc. Hooray! Target your pet and /cheer. Now sit down and heal/med for the next 5 to 6 minutes because the Chief will be back shortly.<br><br>Some info: if the hand to hand close and personal combat with the Chief is to intense, try to FD, but you really shouldn&#8217;t need to. I never once had to FD or flee the Chief solo the 3 levels I camped him, but hey, we have the spell, use it if you need to.<br><br>Also, on buffings. The Chief is a shaman, so he uses quite a few spells as well as melee. See if you can slot Resist Cold and Disease into your buffing chores for both you and the pet (you should already be Shielding yourself and Spirit Armoring you and the pet). Its worth the hassle in HPs saved, trust me. The Chief will root (doesn&#8217;t really hurt you, although it can be a problem if he roots the pet) on occasion, but he really likes using a frost-type DD and disease/poison based spells. The latter really is more of an annoyance unless he gets it on you earlier in the fight. You could Cure Disease if it lasts a long time, but I usually just waited the spell effect out.<br><br>Another note, he will not run, even when you are level 20 and tearing him apart. If you pull him right he will die at your feet, and the other orcs won&#8217;t do a thing. This makes the Chief very easy to solo, even though he will be 2 levels above you at 17. Also, as long as you keep back to the zone wall, you will never see or pull any uber-undead at night in Kithicor.<br> <br>Loot on the Chief basically, well, sucks. A plat rarely, occasional gold pieces, and usually a few silver and copper. The Orc Scalps are useful for a faction quest in High Hold, but they drop little else of value. All the faction hits on these guys are good.<br><br>I camped him for an insurance bubble into 20 and then moved on to Cordelia Minister in North Karana. Use similar Chief tactics, but keep her feared. You should easily have the massive amount of mana to chain-fear her whilst tossing on DOTs and watching your pet beat her down. She spawns near the Wizard Spires&#8230;so watch out for Queynos patrolling guards; if you hunt her and hunted Trissa, you will be KOS with them. Look before pulling, and get her away from the Spires/roadways.<br><br>If you have any questions or problems with this guide, send me an email. Good luck.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Happy Hunting,<br>Kith</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
