<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96661189224648></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96661189224648><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=14&mid=96661189224648>Obscure</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=14&mid=96661189224648#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 11:18 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.80]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Because of the pathing and low aggro range, Kurn's tower on Kunark in the field of bone, in my opinion is the prime spot for Necromancers who want to solo from levels 12 to 16.  Not only will you get good exp and loot, but you will get those essential ingredients to create the ever saving and best friend of a Necro, the Skelli pet.  Though travel is difficult, the reward is great.<br>You will not find a town close to sell if you are not a Iksar, so take a few backpacks make a couple of lizard friends, and prepare to make sacrifices on items.  I stayed in the tower from level 12 to 16 without going to town, its just a matter of selecting and taking what you need, and deleting or giving away copper.  Remember to bind just outside of the entrance to Kurn's tower, so if you need to gate, its not to far back in, and you won't have to worry about being KOS.<br><br>Kill anything which cons even to one level above yours (yellow on my screen).  It will take some practice, but it will be the easiest and fastest way to gain your levels.  If you get extremely bored, kill blues (this is a waste of mana, and I would recommend saving it for the tougher ones).<br><br>Here is my strategy: First I'd cast invis dead on myself and study the pathing of the patrolling skellis.  I would then conjure my pet, command him to guard the spot (not guard me) and then test the corner that I found to make sure when something passed I was out of range.  (note:  The Skelli type will not attack your pet and your pet will not attack the Skellis.)  I stuck mostly to the first floor and up, never down in the basement when soloing.  Pay attention to your surroundings when choosing a target, and stay close to the corner, you will keep trains from a couple to none and people will like you, not to mention you will avoid death.  **This is where the fun begins.**  When you have the target in sight (notice I say sight and not right next to it) cast either engulfing darkness or heat blood on the target and run to your corner.  Then sick your skelli on the target when its close.  The target will then attack the skelli, cast your second DOT spell which ever one you didn't use first on the target, and if desired cast leach which will replenish your hp (this will be helpful if attacking multiple or higher levels), then cast fear undead, slap it with a ward undead spell if you can.  And make sure, because it is essential, and can determine life or death sometimes to call your pet off after you fear the target, by doing this you will save many bone chips, mana , time and future pp, by not having to conjure another pet after each fight.  Now sit back meditate and let your DOTs do all the work.  Make sure to watch your message screen, because when the fear spell wears off, you will want stand up and watch for the targets return, *you will be attacked when it returns, pet or no pet, its pissed and wants to rip the skanky flesh from your bones* (note: time on the fear spell series is totally random).  If you watch close enough after the fear spell wears off, you can usually hit it with another ward undead or lifedraw spell before it attacks you.  When the target arrives, it will usually be a short melee round with the added cast of a lifedraw or ward undead spell.<br><br>If you enjoy soloing and a wide selection of targets, and practically no trains, then this is the place for you.  I don't guarantee success the first time, but with practice, testing and following the above steps to the T, you will have an enjoyable, fun ride through four levels.  After I found this trick, all I could do was laugh and say to my friends, I didn't know it could be this easy.  Oh, and if the Tower is filled with Necro's when you get there, you must not have been the only one to read this, because when I was there, the tower between off times and prime time was between 0 to 12 players.<br><br>Tip:  The higher up you go, the better selection you'll get, and not as many PC's to contend for kills with.<br><br>Obscure<br>lvl 16<br>Terris-Thule<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
